elements.name: Survey6 Introduction
elements.html:
Welcome to the Military Triage Delegation Experiment - Phase 2. Here you will have the chance to review the decisions of other medical professionals in difficult triage scenarios to assess whether you would delegate a triage situation in the future to those decision makers.

In this phase, you will see scenarios where medics made decisions about whether to move to treat casualties or wait in their current location based on the tactical situation.

Each scenario is presented followed by how different medics carried out their assessment and decision-making for that situation. Their choices are listed showing what they decided to do in each probe scenario.

Each medic vignette is then followed by a few questions to assess how you perceived the medic's decision-making style.

While you work your way through each vignette imagine you have seen a lot of other observations of this medic, and the behavior you see here is typical for how they behave.

Please pay careful attention to what information is revealed to the decision maker, and consider their actions only with respect to the information they were given.

The survey should take about 20-30 minutes to complete. Thank you for your participation.

elements.name: Note
elements.html:
Note that in some scenarios, there are buttons that expand/select the information for the medic and the patients.

Note that you can hit the "previous" button if you want to go back to any part of the survey.

elements.name: Test medic 1
elements.title: Phase 2 Mockup
elements.scenarioDescription: Imagine that you are deployed as a military medic in a foreign country. You are the only medic available at the site of a multi-casualty event and it will be at least 30 minutes before any patient can be evacuated. There are two patients, Patient A and Patient B, and you only have time to treat one of them.

rows.probe_unstructured:
Patient A has a chest wound and is gasping for breath. They triggered an IED by poking a suspicious package they had been warned not to touch. The resulting explosion seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has a dislocated left knee with no bleeding. They are a bystander who was injured.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has a chest wound and is gasping for breath. They were goofing around and threw a stapler that hit some electrical equipment, setting off an explosion that seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has a dislocated right knee with no bleeding. They were injured in the accident.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their right foot. They sabotaged a train and seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has a compound fracture above their left elbow with mild bleeding. They were injured in the incident.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their left foot. They triggered a package bomb by shaking a suspicious package they had been warned not to touch. The resulting explosion seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has a compound fracture above their left elbow with mild bleeding. They are a bystander who was injured.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their left foot. They detonated a large IED, killing 1 person and seriously injuring 5 people.
Patient B has moderate bleeding from their left bicep. They are a bystander who was injured.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their right hand. They are a drunk driver who hit a bus, killing 1 person and seriously injuring 5 people.
Patient B has moderate bleeding from their right hip. They were injured in the crash.
Which patient do you treat?

elements.name: Test medic 1
elements.title: Phase 2 Mockup
elements.scenarioDescription: Imagine that you are deployed as a military medic in a foreign country. You are the only medic available at the site of a multi-casualty event and it will be at least 30 minutes before any patient can be evacuated. There are two patients, Patient A and Patient B, and you only have time to treat one of them.

rows.probe_unstructured:
Patient A has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their left hand. They sabotaged a ferry and seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their left foot. They were injured in the incident.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has a chest wound and is gasping for breath. They were goofing around and threw a stapler that hit some electrical equipment, setting off an explosion that seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their left hand. They were injured in the accident.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has moderate bleeding from their left bicep. They detonated a large IED, killing 1 person and seriously injuring 5 people.
Patient B has a compound fracture above their right elbow with mild bleeding. They are a bystander who was injured.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has moderate bleeding from their left thigh. They are a drunk driver who hit a bus, killing 1 person and seriously injuring 5 people.
Patient B has a broken left arm with no bleeding. They were injured in the crash.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has started showing signs of compensated shock (high heart rate, fast breathing). Their bleeding was stopped after a large blood loss. They put a smoke grenade into a tent as a joke and seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has a broken left arm with no bleeding. They were injured in the accident.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their right foot. They are a driver who nodded off behind the wheel, causing an accident that seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has a broken right arm with no bleeding. They were injured in the crash.
Which patient do you treat?

There are two patients, Patient A and Patient B, and you only have time to treat one of them.

rows.probe_unstructured:
Patient A has moderate bleeding from their right thigh. They are a foreign civilian who used to be a member of the opponent military.
Patient B has a dislocated right knee with no bleeding. They are a warfighter in the same military unit as you.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has moderate bleeding from their left forearm. They are a US warfighter from a different branch of the military than you.
Patient B has a broken right arm with no bleeding. They are a warfighter in the same military unit as you.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has started showing signs of compensated shock (high heart rate, fast breathing). Their bleeding was stopped after a large blood loss. They are a foreign civilian contractor who has been working with your unit.
Patient B has a dislocated left knee with no bleeding. They are a warfighter in the same military unit as you.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their left foot. They are a foreign civilian who used to be a member of the opponent military.
Patient B has moderate bleeding from their right hip. They are a warfighter in the same military unit as you.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their right hand. They are a foreign civilian contractor who works for the US military, but not your unit.
Patient B has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their right foot. They are a warfighter in the same military unit as you.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their right hand. They are a foreign civilian contractor who works for the US military, but not your unit.
Patient B has a compound fracture of their right forearm with mild bleeding. They are a warfighter in the same military unit as you.
Which patient do you treat?

elements.scenarioDescription: Imagine that you are deployed as a military medic in a foreign country. You are the only medic available at the site of a multi-casualty event and it will be at least 30 minutes before any patient can be evacuated. There are two patients, Patient A and Patient B, and you only have time to treat one of them.

rows.probe_unstructured:
Patient A has a chest wound and is gasping for breath. They triggered an IED by poking a suspicious package they had been warned not to touch. The resulting explosion seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has a dislocated left knee with no bleeding. They are a bystander who was injured.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has a chest wound and is gasping for breath. They were goofing around and threw a stapler that hit some electrical equipment, setting off an explosion that seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has a dislocated right knee with no bleeding. They were injured in the accident.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their right foot. They sabotaged a train and seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has a compound fracture above their left elbow with mild bleeding. They were injured in the incident.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their left foot. They triggered a package bomb by shaking a suspicious package they had been warned not to touch. The resulting explosion seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has a compound fracture above their left elbow with mild bleeding. They are a bystander who was injured.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their left foot. They detonated a large IED, killing 1 person and seriously injuring 5 people.
Patient B has moderate bleeding from their left bicep. They are a bystander who was injured.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their right hand. They are a drunk driver who hit a bus, killing 1 person and seriously injuring 5 people.
Patient B has moderate bleeding from their right hip. They were injured in the crash.
Which patient do you treat?

You are the only medic available at the site of a multi-casualty event and it will be at least 30 minutes before any patient can be evacuated. There are two patients, Patient A and Patient B, and you only have time to treat one of them.

rows.probe_unstructured:
Patient A has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their right hand. They were horsing around on the job, leading to an accident that seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has a dislocated left knee with no bleeding. They were injured in the accident.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has a chest wound and is gasping for breath. They were goofing around and threw a stapler that hit some electrical equipment, setting off an explosion that seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has a compound fracture above their left elbow with mild bleeding. They were injured in the accident.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their right foot. They pulled an obviously dangerous prank and seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has moderate bleeding from their left forearm. They were injured in the prank.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their right foot. They sabotaged a train and seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their right foot. They were injured in the incident.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has a chest wound and is gasping for breath. They triggered an IED by poking a suspicious package they had been warned not to touch. The resulting explosion seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their left hand. They are a bystander who was injured.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has moderate bleeding from their right forearm. They put a smoke grenade into a tent as a joke and seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has a compound fracture of their left forearm with mild bleeding. They were injured in the accident.
Which patient do you treat?

elements.scenarioDescription: Imagine that you are deployed as a military medic in a foreign country. You arrive at a scene where you know there may be multiple casualties. It will be at least 30 minutes before any casualty can be evacuated and you are the only medic available.

rows.choice: Move to find and treat a different patient
rows.probe_unstructured:
The first casualty you come upon has a dislocated right knee with no bleeding. 
As you finish performing the most immediate treatment on your current patient, someone you know and trust comes to tell you that there is a casualty out of sight who is bleeding a lot.
Do you continue treating your current patient, or do you move to find and treat a different patient?

The first casualty you come upon has a broken right arm with no bleeding. 
As you finish performing the most immediate treatment on your current patient, you hear thumps or sounds from something or someone falling out of sight.
Do you continue treating your current patient, or do you move to find and treat a different patient?

The first casualty you come upon has a compound fracture above their left elbow with mild bleeding. 
As you finish performing the most immediate treatment on your current patient, someone you know and trust comes to tell you that there is a casualty out of sight who is bleeding a lot.
Do you continue treating your current patient, or do you move to find and treat a different patient?

The first casualty you come upon has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their left foot. 
As you finish performing the most immediate treatment on your current patient, you hear someone out of sight who is calling for a medic, and they describe a casualty who isn't breathing.
Do you continue treating your current patient, or do you move to find and treat a different patient?

rows.choice: Move to find and treat a different patient
rows.probe_unstructured:
The first casualty you come upon has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their right hand. 
As you finish performing the most immediate treatment on your current patient, you hear someone out of sight who is shouting "Help! Help!".
Do you continue treating your current patient, or do you move to find and treat a different patient?

rows.choice: Move to find and treat a different patient
rows.probe_unstructured:
The first casualty you come upon has a chest wound and is gasping for breath. 
As you finish performing the most immediate treatment on your current patient, you are told that this casualty was removed from the passenger side of a wrecked vehicle, but the driver is still missing.
Do you continue treating your current patient, or do you move to find and treat a different patient?

elements.title: Phase 2 Mockup
options: Move to find and treat a different patient
elements.scenarioDescription: Imagine that you are deployed as a military medic in a foreign country. You arrive at a scene where you know there may be multiple casualties. It will be at least 30 minutes before any casualty can be evacuated and you are the only medic available.

rows.choice: Move to find and treat a different patient
rows.probe_unstructured:
The first casualty you come upon has a dislocated right knee with no bleeding. 
As you finish performing the most immediate treatment on your current patient, someone you know and trust comes to tell you that there is a casualty out of sight who is bleeding a lot.
Do you continue treating your current patient, or do you move to find and treat a different patient?

The first casualty you come upon has a broken right arm with no bleeding. 
As you finish performing the most immediate treatment on your current patient, you hear thumps or sounds from something or someone falling out of sight.
Do you continue treating your current patient, or do you move to find and treat a different patient?

rows.choice: Move to find and treat a different patient
rows.probe_unstructured:
The first casualty you come upon has a compound fracture above their left elbow with mild bleeding. 
As you finish performing the most immediate treatment on your current patient, someone you know and trust comes to tell you that there is a casualty out of sight who is bleeding a lot.
Do you continue treating your current patient, or do you move to find and treat a different patient?

The first casualty you come upon has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their left foot. 
As you finish performing the most immediate treatment on your current patient, you hear someone out of sight who is calling for a medic, and they describe a casualty who isn't breathing.
Do you continue treating your current patient, or do you move to find and treat a different patient?

rows.choice: Move to find and treat a different patient
rows.probe_unstructured:
The first casualty you come upon has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their right hand. 
As you finish performing the most immediate treatment on your current patient, you hear someone out of sight who is shouting "Help! Help!".
Do you continue treating your current patient, or do you move to find and treat a different patient?

rows.choice: Move to find and treat a different patient
rows.probe_unstructured:
The first casualty you come upon has a chest wound and is gasping for breath. 
As you finish performing the most immediate treatment on your current patient, you are told that this casualty was removed from the passenger side of a wrecked vehicle, but the driver is still missing.
Do you continue treating your current patient, or do you move to find and treat a different patient?

elements.scenarioDescription: Imagine that you are deployed as a military medic in a foreign country. You are the only medic with your unit. It will be at least 30 minutes before any casualty can be evacuated.

rows.probe_unstructured:
Your squad is patrolling dismounted when it receives fire from a sniper and sustains one casualty. Your unit does not have a good idea of the suspected sniper location. You have not received any additional fire in the last 5 minutes.
The casualty is in an exposed location and you would need to move across 100 ft of exposed area to reach them. They are not visible from your location.
You are currently in a location with cover. Do you move to treat the casualty now, or wait in your current location?

Your platoon is patrolling dismounted when your point squad encounters what seems to be an observation post and sustains one casualty. Your squad exchanged fire. Three enemy troops are reported fleeing the location. You have not received any additional fire in the last 2 minutes.
The casualty is in a location with cover, but you would need to move across 20 ft of exposed area to reach them. They are not visible from your location.
You are currently in a location with cover. Do you move to treat the casualty now, or wait in your current location?

In the process of attacking a suspected enemy position, your platoon is pinned down by a heavy volume of fire and sustains one casualty. The enemy fire ceases. You have not received any enemy fire in the last 3 minutes.
The casualty is in a location with cover, but you would need to move across 20 ft of exposed area to reach them. They are not visible from your location.
You are currently in a location with cover. Do you move to treat the casualty now, or wait in your current location?

The casualty is in an exposed location and you would need to move across 100 ft of exposed area to reach them. They are bleeding heavily.
You are currently in a location with cover. Do you move to treat the casualty now, or wait in your current location?

Your platoon is patrolling dismounted when your point squad encounters what seems to be an observation post and sustains one casualty. Your squad exchanged fire. You have not received any additional fire in the last 2 minutes.
The casualty is in an exposed location and you would need to move across 100 ft of exposed area to reach them. They are bleeding heavily.

elements.name: Test medic 1
elements.title: Phase 2 Mockup
elements.scenarioDescription: Imagine that you are deployed as a military medic in a foreign country. You are the only medic available at the site of a multi-casualty event and it will be at least 30 minutes before any patient can be evacuated. There are two patients, Patient A and Patient B, and you only have time to treat one of them.

rows.probe_unstructured:
Patient A has a chest wound and is gasping for breath. They triggered an IED by poking a suspicious package they had been warned not to touch. The resulting explosion seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has a dislocated left knee with no bleeding. They are a bystander who was injured.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has a chest wound and is gasping for breath. They were goofing around and threw a stapler that hit some electrical equipment, setting off an explosion that seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has a dislocated right knee with no bleeding. They were injured in the accident.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their right foot. They sabotaged a train and seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has a compound fracture above their left elbow with mild bleeding. They were injured in the incident.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their left foot. They triggered a package bomb by shaking a suspicious package they had been warned not to touch. The resulting explosion seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has a compound fracture above their left elbow with mild bleeding. They are a bystander who was injured.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their left foot. They detonated a large IED, killing 1 person and seriously injuring 5 people.
Patient B has moderate bleeding from their left bicep. They are a bystander who was injured.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their right hand. They are a drunk driver who hit a bus, killing 1 person and seriously injuring 5 people.
Patient B has moderate bleeding from their right hip. They were injured in the crash.
Which patient do you treat?

elements.name: Test medic 1
elements.title: Phase 2 Mockup
elements.scenarioDescription: Imagine that you are deployed as a military medic in a foreign country. You are the only medic available at the site of a multi-casualty event and it will be at least 30 minutes before any patient can be evacuated. There are two patients, Patient A and Patient B, and you only have time to treat one of them.

rows.probe_unstructured:
Patient A has moderate bleeding from their right thigh. They are a foreign civilian who used to be a member of the opponent military.
Patient B has a dislocated right knee with no bleeding. They are a warfighter in the same military unit as you.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has moderate bleeding from their left forearm. They are a US warfighter from a different branch of the military than you.
Patient B has a broken right arm with no bleeding. They are a warfighter in the same military unit as you.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has started showing signs of compensated shock (high heart rate, fast breathing). Their bleeding was stopped after a large blood loss. They are a foreign civilian contractor who has been working with your unit.
Patient B has a dislocated left knee with no bleeding. They are a warfighter in the same military unit as you.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their left foot. They are a foreign civilian who used to be a member of the opponent military.
Patient B has moderate bleeding from their right hip. They are a warfighter in the same military unit as you.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their right hand. They are a foreign civilian contractor who works for the US military, but not your unit.
Patient B has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their right foot. They are a warfighter in the same military unit as you.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their right hand. They are a foreign civilian contractor who works for the US military, but not your unit.
Patient B has a compound fracture of their right forearm with mild bleeding. They are a warfighter in the same military unit as you.
Which patient do you treat?

elements.title: Phase 2 Mockup
elements.scenarioDescription: Imagine that you are deployed as a military medic in a foreign country. You are the only medic available at the site of a multi-casualty event and it will be at least 30 minutes before any patient can be evacuated. There are two patients, Patient A and Patient B, and you only have time to treat one of them.

rows.probe_unstructured:
Patient A has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their right hand. They were horsing around on the job, leading to an accident that seriously injured 2 people.

Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has a chest wound and is gasping for breath. They were goofing around and threw a stapler that hit some electrical equipment, setting off an explosion that seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has a compound fracture above their left elbow with mild bleeding. They were injured in the accident.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their right foot. They pulled an obviously dangerous prank and seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has moderate bleeding from their left forearm. They were injured in the prank.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their right foot. They sabotaged a train and seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their right foot. They were injured in the incident.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has a chest wound and is gasping for breath. They triggered an IED by poking a suspicious package they had been warned not to touch. The resulting explosion seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their left hand. They are a bystander who was injured.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has moderate bleeding from their right forearm. They put a smoke grenade into a tent as a joke and seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has a compound fracture of their left forearm with mild bleeding. They were injured in the accident.
Which patient do you treat?

elements.name: Test medic 1
elements.title: Phase 2 Mockup
options: Move to find and treat a different patient
elements.scenarioDescription: Imagine that you are deployed as a military medic in a foreign country. You arrive at a scene where you know there may be multiple casualties. It will be at least 30 minutes before any casualty can be evacuated and you are the only medic available.

rows.choice: Move to find and treat a different patient
rows.probe_unstructured:
The first casualty you come upon has a dislocated right knee with no bleeding. 
As you finish performing the most immediate treatment on your current patient, someone you know and trust comes to tell you that there is a casualty out of sight who is bleeding a lot.
Do you continue treating your current patient, or do you move to find and treat a different patient?

rows.choice: Move to find and treat a different patient
rows.probe_unstructured:
The first casualty you come upon has a broken right arm with no bleeding. 
As you finish performing the most immediate treatment on your current patient, you hear thumps or sounds from something or someone falling out of sight.
Do you continue treating your current patient, or do you move to find and treat a different patient?

rows.choice: Move to find and treat a different patient
rows.probe_unstructured:
The first casualty you come upon has a compound fracture above their left elbow with mild bleeding. 
As you finish performing the most immediate treatment on your current patient, someone you know and trust comes to tell you that there is a casualty out of sight who is bleeding a lot.
Do you continue treating your current patient, or do you move to find and treat a different patient?

The first casualty you come upon has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their left foot. 
As you finish performing the most immediate treatment on your current patient, you hear someone out of sight who is calling for a medic, and they describe a casualty who isn't breathing.
Do you continue treating your current patient, or do you move to find and treat a different patient?

The first casualty you come upon has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their right hand. 
As you finish performing the most immediate treatment on your current patient, you hear someone out of sight who is shouting "Help! Help!".
Do you continue treating your current patient, or do you move to find and treat a different patient?

The first casualty you come upon has a chest wound and is gasping for breath. 
As you finish performing the most immediate treatment on your current patient, you are told that this casualty was removed from the passenger side of a wrecked vehicle, but the driver is still missing.
Do you continue treating your current patient, or do you move to find and treat a different patient?

elements.scenarioDescription: Imagine that you are deployed as a military medic in a foreign country. You arrive at a scene where you know there may be multiple casualties. It will be at least 30 minutes before any casualty can be evacuated and you are the only medic available.

rows.choice: Move to find and treat a different patient
rows.probe_unstructured:
The first casualty you come upon has a dislocated right knee with no bleeding. 
As you finish performing the most immediate treatment on your current patient, someone you know and trust comes to tell you that there is a casualty out of sight who is bleeding a lot.
Do you continue treating your current patient, or do you move to find and treat a different patient?

rows.choice: Move to find and treat a different patient
rows.probe_unstructured:
The first casualty you come upon has a broken right arm with no bleeding. 
As you finish performing the most immediate treatment on your current patient, you hear thumps or sounds from something or someone falling out of sight.
Do you continue treating your current patient, or do you move to find and treat a different patient?

rows.choice: Move to find and treat a different patient
rows.probe_unstructured:
The first casualty you come upon has a compound fracture above their left elbow with mild bleeding. 
As you finish performing the most immediate treatment on your current patient, someone you know and trust comes to tell you that there is a casualty out of sight who is bleeding a lot.
Do you continue treating your current patient, or do you move to find and treat a different patient?

The first casualty you come upon has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their left foot. 
As you finish performing the most immediate treatment on your current patient, you hear someone out of sight who is calling for a medic, and they describe a casualty who isn't breathing.
Do you continue treating your current patient, or do you move to find and treat a different patient?

The first casualty you come upon has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their right hand. 
As you finish performing the most immediate treatment on your current patient, you hear someone out of sight who is shouting "Help! Help!".
Do you continue treating your current patient, or do you move to find and treat a different patient?

The first casualty you come upon has a chest wound and is gasping for breath. 
As you finish performing the most immediate treatment on your current patient, you are told that this casualty was removed from the passenger side of a wrecked vehicle, but the driver is still missing.
Do you continue treating your current patient, or do you move to find and treat a different patient?

elements.scenarioDescription: Imagine that you are deployed as a military medic in a foreign country. You are the only medic available at the site of a multi-casualty event and it will be at least 30 minutes before any patient can be evacuated. There are two patients, Patient A and Patient B, and you only have time to treat one of them.

rows.probe_unstructured:
Patient A has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their right hand. They were horsing around on the job, leading to an accident that seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has a dislocated left knee with no bleeding. They were injured in the accident.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has a chest wound and is gasping for breath. They were goofing around and threw a stapler that hit some electrical equipment, setting off an explosion that seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has a compound fracture above their left elbow with mild bleeding. They were injured in the accident.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their right foot. They pulled an obviously dangerous prank and seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has moderate bleeding from their left forearm. They were injured in the prank.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their right foot. They sabotaged a train and seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their right foot. They were injured in the incident.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has a chest wound and is gasping for breath. They triggered an IED by poking a suspicious package they had been warned not to touch. The resulting explosion seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their left hand. They are a bystander who was injured.
Which patient do you treat?

elements.title: Phase 2 Mockup
elements.scenarioDescription: Imagine that you are deployed as a military medic in a foreign country. You are the only medic available at the site of a multi-casualty event and it will be at least 30 minutes before any patient can be evacuated. There are two patients, Patient A and Patient B, and you only have time to treat one of them.

rows.probe_unstructured:
Patient A has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their left hand. They sabotaged a ferry and seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their left foot. They were injured in the incident.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has a chest wound and is gasping for breath. They were goofing around and threw a stapler that hit some electrical equipment, setting off an explosion that seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their left hand. They were injured in the accident.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has moderate bleeding from their left bicep. They detonated a large IED, killing 1 person and seriously injuring 5 people.
Patient B has a compound fracture above their right elbow with mild bleeding. They are a bystander who was injured.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has moderate bleeding from their left thigh. They are a drunk driver who hit a bus, killing 1 person and seriously injuring 5 people.
Patient B has a broken left arm with no bleeding. They were injured in the crash.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has started showing signs of compensated shock (high heart rate, fast breathing). Their bleeding was stopped after a large blood loss. They put a smoke grenade into a tent as a joke and seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has a broken left arm with no bleeding. They were injured in the accident.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their right foot. They are a driver who nodded off behind the wheel, causing an accident that seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has a broken right arm with no bleeding. They were injured in the crash.
Which patient do you treat?

options: Move to treat the casualty now
elements.scenarioDescription: Imagine that you are deployed as a military medic in a foreign country. You are the only medic with your unit. It will be at least 30 minutes before any casualty can be evacuated.

rows.choice: Move to treat the casualty now
rows.probe_unstructured:
Your squad is patrolling dismounted when it receives fire from a sniper and sustains one casualty. Your unit does not have a good idea of the suspected sniper location. You have not received any additional fire in the last 5 minutes.
The casualty is in an exposed location and you would need to move across 100 ft of exposed area to reach them. They are not visible from your location.
You are currently in a location with cover. Do you move to treat the casualty now, or wait in your current location?

Your platoon is patrolling dismounted when your point squad encounters what seems to be an observation post and sustains one casualty. Your squad exchanged fire. Three enemy troops are reported fleeing the location. You have not received any additional fire in the last 2 minutes.
The casualty is in a location with cover, but you would need to move across 20 ft of exposed area to reach them. They are not visible from your location.
You are currently in a location with cover. Do you move to treat the casualty now, or wait in your current location?

rows.choice: Move to treat the casualty now
rows.probe_unstructured:

You are currently in a location with cover. Do you move to treat the casualty now, or wait in your current location?

elements.title: Phase 2 Mockup
options: Move to treat the casualty now
elements.scenarioDescription: Imagine that you are deployed as a military medic in a foreign country. You are the only medic with your unit. It will be at least 30 minutes before any casualty can be evacuated.

rows.choice: Move to treat the casualty now
rows.probe_unstructured:
Your squad is patrolling dismounted when it receives fire from a sniper and sustains one casualty. Your unit does not have a good idea of the suspected sniper location. You have not received any additional fire in the last 5 minutes.
The casualty is in an exposed location and you would need to move across 100 ft of exposed area to reach them. They are not visible from your location.
You are currently in a location with cover. Do you move to treat the casualty now, or wait in your current location?

Your platoon is patrolling dismounted when your point squad encounters what seems to be an observation post and sustains one casualty. Your squad exchanged fire. Three enemy troops are reported fleeing the location. You have not received any additional fire in the last 2 minutes.
The casualty is in a location with cover, but you would need to move across 20 ft of exposed area to reach them. They are not visible from your location.
You are currently in a location with cover. Do you move to treat the casualty now, or wait in your current location?

rows.choice: Move to treat the casualty now
rows.probe_unstructured:
In the process of attacking a suspected enemy position, your platoon is pinned down by a heavy volume of fire and sustains one casualty. The enemy fire ceases. You have not received any enemy fire in the last 3 minutes.
The casualty is in a location with cover, but you would need to move across 20 ft of exposed area to reach them. They are not visible from your location.
You are currently in a location with cover. Do you move to treat the casualty now, or wait in your current location?

elements.name: Test medic 1
elements.title: Phase 2 Mockup
elements.scenarioDescription: Imagine that you are deployed as a military medic in a foreign country. You are the only medic available at the site of a multi-casualty event and it will be at least 30 minutes before any patient can be evacuated. There are two patients, Patient A and Patient B, and you only have time to treat one of them.

rows.probe_unstructured:
Patient A has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their left hand. They sabotaged a ferry and seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their left foot. They were injured in the incident.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has a chest wound and is gasping for breath. They were goofing around and threw a stapler that hit some electrical equipment, setting off an explosion that seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their left hand. They were injured in the accident.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has moderate bleeding from their left bicep. They detonated a large IED, killing 1 person and seriously injuring 5 people.
Patient B has a compound fracture above their right elbow with mild bleeding. They are a bystander who was injured.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has moderate bleeding from their left thigh. They are a drunk driver who hit a bus, killing 1 person and seriously injuring 5 people.
Patient B has a broken left arm with no bleeding. They were injured in the crash.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has started showing signs of compensated shock (high heart rate, fast breathing). Their bleeding was stopped after a large blood loss. They put a smoke grenade into a tent as a joke and seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has a broken left arm with no bleeding. They were injured in the accident.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their right foot. They are a driver who nodded off behind the wheel, causing an accident that seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has a broken right arm with no bleeding. They were injured in the crash.
Which patient do you treat?

elements.name: Test medic 1
elements.title: Phase 2 Mockup
elements.scenarioDescription: Imagine that you are deployed as a military medic in a foreign country. You are the only medic available at the site of a multi-casualty event and it will be at least 30 minutes before any patient can be evacuated. There are two patients, Patient A and Patient B, and you only have time to treat one of them.

rows.probe_unstructured:
Patient A has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their left hand. They sabotaged a ferry and seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their left foot. They were injured in the incident.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has a chest wound and is gasping for breath. They were goofing around and threw a stapler that hit some electrical equipment, setting off an explosion that seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their left hand. They were injured in the accident.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has moderate bleeding from their left bicep. They detonated a large IED, killing 1 person and seriously injuring 5 people.
Patient B has a compound fracture above their right elbow with mild bleeding. They are a bystander who was injured.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has moderate bleeding from their left thigh. They are a drunk driver who hit a bus, killing 1 person and seriously injuring 5 people.
Patient B has a broken left arm with no bleeding. They were injured in the crash.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has started showing signs of compensated shock (high heart rate, fast breathing). Their bleeding was stopped after a large blood loss. They put a smoke grenade into a tent as a joke and seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has a broken left arm with no bleeding. They were injured in the accident.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their right foot. They are a driver who nodded off behind the wheel, causing an accident that seriously injured 2 people.
Patient B has a broken right arm with no bleeding. They were injured in the crash.
Which patient do you treat?

elements.scenarioDescription: Imagine that you are deployed as a military medic in a foreign country. You are the only medic with your unit. It will be at least 30 minutes before any casualty can be evacuated.

rows.choice: Move to treat the casualty now
rows.probe_unstructured:
Your unit is conducting a mounted patrol on JLTVs when you are ambushed, receiving small arms and RPG fire, and sustaining one casualty. Your unit returns fire at the suspected enemy location. About six enemy troops are spotted withdrawing. You have not received any additional fire in the last 3 minutes.
The casualty is in a location with cover, but you would need to move across 100 ft of exposed area to reach them. They are bleeding heavily.
You are currently in a location with cover. Do you move to treat the casualty now, or wait in your current location?

In the process of attacking a suspected enemy position, your platoon is pinned down by a heavy volume of fire and sustains one casualty. The enemy fire ceases. You have not received any enemy fire in the last 3 minutes.
The casualty is in a location with cover, but you would need to move across 100 ft of exposed area to reach them. They are calling for a help, but you can't see their injury.
You are currently in a location with cover. Do you move to treat the casualty now, or wait in your current location?

options: Move to treat the casualty now
elements.scenarioDescription: Imagine that you are deployed as a military medic in a foreign country. You are the only medic with your unit. It will be at least 30 minutes before any casualty can be evacuated.

rows.choice: Move to treat the casualty now
rows.probe_unstructured:
Your unit is conducting a mounted patrol on JLTVs when you are ambushed, receiving small arms and RPG fire, and sustaining one casualty. Your unit returns fire at the suspected enemy location. About six enemy troops are spotted withdrawing. You have not received any additional fire in the last 3 minutes.
The casualty is in a location with cover, but you would need to move across 100 ft of exposed area to reach them. They are bleeding heavily.
You are currently in a location with cover. Do you move to treat the casualty now, or wait in your current location?

Your squad is patrolling dismounted when it receives fire from a sniper and sustains one casualty. Your unit does not have a good idea of the suspected sniper location. You have not received any additional fire in the last 5 minutes.
The casualty is in an exposed location and you would need to move across 100 ft of exposed area to reach them. They are calling for a help, but you can't see their injury.
You are currently in a location with cover. Do you move to treat the casualty now, or wait in your current location?

rows.choice: Move to treat the casualty now

elements.title: Phase 2 Mockup
elements.scenarioDescription: Imagine that you are deployed as a military medic in a foreign country. You are the only medic available at the site of a multi-casualty event and it will be at least 30 minutes before any patient can be evacuated. There are two patients, Patient A and Patient B, and you only have time to treat one of them.

rows.probe_unstructured:
Patient A has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their left foot. They are a US warfighter from a different branch of the military than you.
Patient B has a dislocated left knee with no bleeding. They are a warfighter in the same military unit as you.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their right hand. They are a foreign civilian contractor who works for the US military, but not your unit.
Patient B has a broken left arm with no bleeding. They are a warfighter in the same military unit as you.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has a chest wound and is gasping for breath. They are a foreign civilian contractor who works for the US military, but not your unit.
Patient B has a compound fracture of their left forearm with mild bleeding. They are a warfighter in the same military unit as you.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their right hand. They are a US civilian contractor who works for the US military.
Patient B has moderate bleeding from their right bicep. They are a warfighter in the same military unit as you.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their right foot. They are a foreign civilian with no ties to the military.
Patient B has moderate bleeding from their left thigh. They are a warfighter in the same military unit as you.
Which patient do you treat?

Patient A has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their left hand. They are a foreign civilian who used to be a member of the opponent military.
Patient B has moderate bleeding from their right thigh. They are a warfighter in the same military unit as you.
Which patient do you treat?

elements.scenarioDescription: Imagine that you are deployed as a military medic in a foreign country. You arrive at a scene where you know there may be multiple casualties. It will be at least 30 minutes before any casualty can be evacuated and you are the only medic available.

rows.probe_unstructured:
The first casualty you come upon has a dislocated right knee with no bleeding. 
As you finish performing the most immediate treatment on your current patient, someone you know and trust comes to tell you that there is a casualty out of sight who is bleeding a lot.
Do you continue treating your current patient, or do you move to find and treat a different patient?

The first casualty you come upon has a broken right arm with no bleeding. 
As you finish performing the most immediate treatment on your current patient, you hear thumps or sounds from something or someone falling out of sight.
Do you continue treating your current patient, or do you move to find and treat a different patient?

The first casualty you come upon has a compound fracture above their left elbow with mild bleeding. 
As you finish performing the most immediate treatment on your current patient, someone you know and trust comes to tell you that there is a casualty out of sight who is bleeding a lot.
Do you continue treating your current patient, or do you move to find and treat a different patient?

The first casualty you come upon has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their left foot. 
As you finish performing the most immediate treatment on your current patient, you hear someone out of sight who is calling for a medic, and they describe a casualty who isn't breathing.
Do you continue treating your current patient, or do you move to find and treat a different patient?

The first casualty you come upon has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their right hand. 
As you finish performing the most immediate treatment on your current patient, you hear someone out of sight who is shouting "Help! Help!".
Do you continue treating your current patient, or do you move to find and treat a different patient?

The first casualty you come upon has a chest wound and is gasping for breath. 
As you finish performing the most immediate treatment on your current patient, you are told that this casualty was removed from the passenger side of a wrecked vehicle, but the driver is still missing.
Do you continue treating your current patient, or do you move to find and treat a different patient?

The first casualty you come upon has a dislocated right knee with no bleeding. 
As you finish performing the most immediate treatment on your current patient, someone you know and trust comes to tell you that there is a casualty out of sight who is bleeding a lot.
Do you continue treating your current patient, or do you move to find and treat a different patient?

The first casualty you come upon has a broken right arm with no bleeding. 
As you finish performing the most immediate treatment on your current patient, you hear thumps or sounds from something or someone falling out of sight.
Do you continue treating your current patient, or do you move to find and treat a different patient?

The first casualty you come upon has a compound fracture above their left elbow with mild bleeding. 
As you finish performing the most immediate treatment on your current patient, someone you know and trust comes to tell you that there is a casualty out of sight who is bleeding a lot.
Do you continue treating your current patient, or do you move to find and treat a different patient?

The first casualty you come upon has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their left foot. 
As you finish performing the most immediate treatment on your current patient, you hear someone out of sight who is calling for a medic, and they describe a casualty who isn't breathing.
Do you continue treating your current patient, or do you move to find and treat a different patient?

The first casualty you come upon has massive bleeding from a partial amputation of their right hand. 
As you finish performing the most immediate treatment on your current patient, you hear someone out of sight who is shouting "Help! Help!".
Do you continue treating your current patient, or do you move to find and treat a different patient?

The first casualty you come upon has a chest wound and is gasping for breath. 
As you finish performing the most immediate treatment on your current patient, you are told that this casualty was removed from the passenger side of a wrecked vehicle, but the driver is still missing.
Do you continue treating your current patient, or do you move to find and treat a different patient?

Do you continue treating your current patient, or do you move to find and treat a different patient?

elements.name: Test medic 1
elements.title: Phase 2 Mockup
options: Move to treat the casualty now
elements.scenarioDescription: Imagine that you are deployed as a military medic in a foreign country. You are the only medic with your unit. It will be at least 30 minutes before any casualty can be evacuated.

rows.choice: Move to treat the casualty now
rows.probe_unstructured:
Your squad is patrolling dismounted when it receives fire from a sniper and sustains one casualty. Your unit does not have a good idea of the suspected sniper location. You have not received any additional fire in the last 5 minutes.
The casualty is in an exposed location and you would need to move across 100 ft of exposed area to reach them. They are not visible from your location.
You are currently in a location with cover. Do you move to treat the casualty now, or wait in your current location?

rows.choice: Move to treat the casualty now
rows.probe_unstructured:
Your platoon is patrolling dismounted when your point squad encounters what seems to be an observation post and sustains one casualty. Your squad exchanged fire. Three enemy troops are reported fleeing the location. You have not received any additional fire in the last 2 minutes.
The casualty is in a location with cover, but you would need to move across 20 ft of exposed area to reach them. They are not visible from your location.
You are currently in a location with cover. Do you move to treat the casualty now, or wait in your current location?

rows.choice: Move to treat the casualty now
rows.probe_unstructured:
In the process of attacking a suspected enemy position, your platoon is pinned down by a heavy volume of fire and sustains one casualty. The enemy fire ceases. You have not received any enemy fire in the last 3 minutes.
The casualty is in a location with cover, but you would need to move across 20 ft of exposed area to reach them. They are not visible from your location.
You are currently in a location with cover. Do you move to treat the casualty now, or wait in your current location?
